"Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Soothill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Soothill (in Dewsbury, WR Yorks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Suttle","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>sotil</i>, <i>sutel</i> ‘subtle, clever, cunning’ (Old French <i>sotil</i>).","habitational name from Soothill in Dewsbury (Yorkshire), from Old English <i>sōt</i> ‘soot’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."]},{"name":"Southwell","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>south</i> ‘south’ + <i>wel(le)</i> ‘well, pool, spring’ (Old English <i>sūth</i> + <i>wella</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived ‘by the south well’ or ‘south of the well’, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Southwell (Nottinghamshire) or Southwell on the Isle of Portland (Dorset).","in Yorkshire and Lancashire, often a hypercorrect form of <b>Soothill</b>, a habitational name from Soothill in Dewsbury (Yorkshire), from Old English <i>sōt</i> ‘soot’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":0,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was origi